[3.2 SQL Data Definition]
    - SQL DDL allows specifictaion of not only a set of relations, but also information about each relation, including:
        1) schema of each relation.
        2) types of values associated with each attribute
        3) integrity constraints
        4) set of indices to be maintained for each relation
        5) security and authorization information for each relation.
        6) physical storage structure of each relation on disk.

    (3.2.1 Basic Types)
        - char: fixed-length character string with user-specified length n. (character)
        - varchar: variable-length character string with user-specified maximum length n. (character varying)
        - int
        - smallint
        - numeric(p, d): fixed-point number, p digits and d of the p digits are to the right of the decimal point.
            ex) numeric(3, 1) -> allows 44.5, 10.0
        - real, double precision
        - float

    (3.2.2 Basic Schema Definition)
        - primary key
            -> nonnull, unique
        - foreign key references
        - not null
